<h2 style="font-family: Quicksand; font-weight: bold; text-align: left; margin-bottom:1rem;">SAT Solver Setup</h2>

<p>A <strong>SAT</strong> (satisfiability) solver takes a logic expression which encodes the rules of the world and returns a model (true and false assignments to logic symbols) that satisfies that expression if such a model exists. To efficiently find a possible model from an expression, we take advantage of the pycosat module (https://pypi.python.org/pypi/pycosat), which is a python wrapper around the picoSAT library (http://fmv.jku.at/picosat/).</p>
<p>Unfortunately, this requires installing this module/library on eachmachine. To install this software on your own machine, please follow these steps:</p>
<p>1. <strong>Install pip</strong> (if you don't have it installed on your system already).Instructions: http://pip.readthedocs.org/en/latest/installing/ (Note:probably requires super-user (sudo) permissions)</p>
<p>2. <strong>Install pycosat</strong>: On command line run: pip install pycosat. (Note: you may need to run: sudo pip install pycosat). There should be no errors.</p>
<p><strong>Testing pycosat installation:</strong></p>
<p>1. After unzipping the project code and changing to the project code directory, run: <span style="color: #ff0000;">python3 pycosat_test.py</span> See pycosat_test.py in the project code. This should output: <span style="color: #ff0000;">[1, -2, -3, -4, 5]</span>.</p>
<p>Please let us know if you have issues with this setup. This is critical to completing the project, and we don't want you to spend your time fighting with this installation process.</p>

<h2 style="font-family: Quicksand; font-weight: bold; text-align: left; margin-bottom:1rem;">The Expr Class</h2>

<p>In this project, you will be working with the <strong>Expr class</strong> defined in <span style="color: #008000;"><strong>logic.py</strong></span> to build propositional logic sentences. An Expr object is implemented as a tree with logical operators ($\land, \lor, \lnot, \Rightarrow, \Leftrightarrow$ ) at each node and with literals (<strong>A, B, C</strong>) at the leaves. The sentence:</p>
<p><strong>$(A \land B) \Leftrightarrow (\lnot C \lor D)$ </strong></p>
<p>would be represented as the tree</p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="350" height="308" style="display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;" /></p>
<p>To instantiate a symbol named 'A', call the constructor like this:</p>
<p><span style="color: #008000;">A = Expr('A')</span></p>
<p>The Expr class allows you to use Python operators to build up these expressions. The following are the available Python operators and their meanings:</p>
<div class="markdown-body">
<ul>
<li>~A: $\lnot A$</li>
<li>A & B: $A \land B$</li>
<li>A | B: $A \lor B$</li>
<li>A >> B: $A \Rightarrow B$</li>
<li>A % B: $A \Leftrightarrow B$</li>
</ul>
</div>
<p>So to build the $A \land B$ expression, you would type this:</p>
<p><span style="color: #008000;">A = Expr('A')</span></p>
<p><span style="color: #008000;">B = Expr('B')</span></p>
<p><span style="color: #008000;">a_and_b = A &amp; B</span></p>
<p>(Note that A to the left of the assignment operator in that example is just a Python variable name, i.e. <span style="color: #008000;">symbol1 = Expr('A')</span> would have worked just as well.)</p>
<p>One last important thing to note is that typing in <span style="color: #008000;">A &amp; B &amp; C</span> will give the expression <span style="color: #008000;">((A &amp; B) &amp; C)</span>. If instead you want <span style="color: #008000;">(A &amp; B &amp; C)</span>, as you will for these problems, use <span style="color: #008000;">logic.conjoin</span>, which takes a list of expressions as input and returns one expression that is the conjunction of all the inputs. The &amp; operator in Python is a binary operator and builds an unbalanced binary tree if you chain it several times,whereas conjoin builds a tree that is one level deep with all the inputs extending directly from the &amp; operator at the root. logic.disjoin is similarly defined for |. The autograder for Question 1 will require that you use logic.conjoin and logic.disjoin wherever you could otherwise chain several &amp; operators or several | operators. If you keep with this convention for later problems, it will help with debugging because you will get more readable expressions.</p>
<p>There is additional, more detailed documentation for the Expr classin logic.py.</p>
<p><span style="font-size: large;"><strong>Tips</strong></span></p>
<div class="markdown-body">
<ul>
<li>When creating a symbol with Expr, it must start with an upper case character. You will get non-obvious errors later if you don't follow this convention. </li>
<li>Be careful creating and combining Expr instances. For example, if you intend to do <span style="color: #008000;">x = Expr('A')&amp;Expr('B')</span>, you don't want to accidentally type <span style="color: #008000;">x = Expr('A&amp;B').</span> The former with be a logical expression of the symbol 'A' and the symbol 'B', while the latter will be a single symbol (Expr) named 'A&amp;B'.</li>
</ul>
</div>

<h2 style="font-family: Quicksand; font-weight: bold; text-align: left; margin-bottom:1rem;">Question 2 (2 points): Logic Workout</h2>

<p><span style="font-size: small;">Implement the following three logic expressions in <span style="color: #ff0000;">logicPlan.py:</span></span></p>
<div class="markdown-body"><ul>
<li><span style="font-size: small; color: #000000;"><span style="color: #008000;">atLeastOne(literals):</span> Return a single expression (Expr) in CNF that is true only if at least one expression in the input list is true. Each input expression will be a literal.</span></li>
<li><span style="font-size: small; color: #000000;"><span style="color: #008000;">atMostOne(literals):</span> Return a single expression (Expr) in CNF that is true only if at most one expression in the input list is true. Each input expression will be a literal.</span></li>
<li><span style="font-size: small; color: #000000;"><span style="color: #008000;">exactlyOne(literals):</span> Return a single expression (Expr) in CNF that is true only if exactly one expression in the input list is true. Each input expression will be a literal.</span></li>
</ul></div>
<p><span style="font-size: small; color: #000000;">Each of these methods takes a list of <span style="color: #008000;">logic.Expr</span> literals and returns a single <span style="color: #008000;">logic.Expr</span> expression that represents the appropriate logical relationship between the expressions in the input list. An additional requirement is that the returned Expr must be in CNF (conjunctivenormal form). <strong>You may NOT use the logic.to_cnf function in your method implementations (or any of the helper functions logic.eliminate_implications, logic.move_not_inwards, and logic.distribute_and_over_or).</strong></span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: small; color: #000000;">When implementing your planning agents in the later questions,you will not have to worry about CNF until right before sending your expression to the SAT solver (at which point you can use <span style="color: #008000;">findModel</span> from question 1). <span style="color: #008000;">logic.to_cnf</span> implements the algorithm from section 7.5 in AIMA. However, on certain worst-case inputs, the direct implementation of this algorithm can result in an exponentially sized sentences. In fact, a certain non-CNF implementation of one of these three functions is one such worst case. So if you find yourself needing the functionality of <span style="color: #008000;">atLeastOne, atMostOne, or exactlyOne</span> for a later question, make sure to use the functions you've already implemented here to avoid accidentally coming up with that non-CNF alternative and passing it to <span style="color: #008000;">logic.to_cnf</span>. If you do this, your code will be so slow that you can't even solve a 3x3 maze with no walls.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-size: small; color: #000000;">You may utilize the<span style="color: #008000;"> logic.pl_true</span> function to test the output of your expressions. <span style="color: #008000;">pl_true</span> takes an expression and a model and returns True if and only if the expression is true given the model. </span></p>

<h2 style="font-family: Quicksand; font-weight: bold; text-align: left; margin-bottom:1rem;">Question 3 (1 point): Extract the Solution</h2>

<p><span style="font-size: small;">In future questions you will be assembling logic expression to pass to a SAT solver. The SAT solver returns a model that will cause the logic expressions to be true. In the Pacman world, we need to convert this model into a specific sequence of actions ('North', 'South', 'East', 'West') that will lead Pacman to the goal.</span></p>
<p>Implement the following function in<span style="color: #008000;"> logicPlan.py</span>:</p>
<div class="markdown-body"><ul>
<li><span style="color: #008000;">extractActionSequence(model, actions):</span> Returns a ordered sequence of action strings based on the given model.</li>
</ul></div>
<p>The function definition has been started for you in <span style="color: #008000;">logicPlan.py</span>. Do not change the function signature.</p>
<p>A model is a dictionary of the symbols in your expression and a corresponding assignment of True or False. The keys in the model dictionary will be symbols in the form of a <span style="color: #008000;">logic.PropSymbolExpr.</span> The model will contain assignments of True/False to many different symbols used in the Pacman world. Within the many symbols in the model, some of them will be action symbols. Each action will have a different symbol for each time point. For example 'East[3]', represents the symbol for taking the action 'East' at time t=3. This method must find the actions symbols that are true in the model and return an ordered list of action strings. The variable <span style="color: #008000;">actions</span> contain all of the possible actions that could be taken at any time point. Each action symbol will follow the very specific format of <span style="color: #008000;">action_string[t]</span> where<span style="color: #008000;"> action_string</span> is one ofactions and t will range from 0 to max_time-1.</p>
<p>For your convenience, the <span style="color: #008000;">logic.PropSymbolExpr</span> class has a static method <span style="color: #008000;">parseExpr</span> which will do the regex parsing of a symbol in one of these formats for you. Look at that function in <span style="color: #008000;">logic.py</span> to read its output format.</p>

<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="color: #ff0000;"><strong>&gt; python autograder.py -q q3</strong></span></p>
